	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037437150?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {This paper focuses on the adaptive path planning problem for torpedoes in complex seabed environments characterized by irregular terrain elevation, clustered obstacles, and narrow passages. The goal is to improve navigation efficiency and safety by optimizing the obstacle avoidance and generalization performance of the path planning algorithm under these challenging conditions. Based on underwater vehicle path planning principles, this study employs the A* algorithm as the core path planning technique and improves path search efficiency through the design of multiple heuristic functions and cost weights. The experiments were conducted on the MATLAB platform, where various heuristic functions (e.g., Chebyshev and Euclidean distances) were compared, and weight parameters were optimized using automated testing scripts. Results indicate that the weight combination [Cg, Ch]=[0.3,0.8] achieved the best overall performance, significantly enhancing path planning efficiency and obstacle avoidance. Additionally, the planned path was further smoothed and optimized using spline fitting and a genetic algorithm (GA), ensuring higher feasibility and reduced path length. This work highlights the potential of combining heuristic search, parameter optimization, and evolutionary algorithms for intelligent path planning, contributing to the broader field of signal processing and intelligent computation. © 2025 IEEE.},
